  "text": "Through a comprehensive audit of the pandas-dev/pandas repository, I identified four Python source files that contain runtime dependencies on scipy.stats via direct `from scipy.stats import` statements:\n\n1. **pandas/plotting/_matplotlib/misc.py** (line 83): Imports `gaussian_kde` for KDE (kernel density estimation) visualization in scatter plot diagonals.\n\n2. **pandas/plotting/_matplotlib/hist.py** (line 275): Imports `gaussian_kde` for KDE histogram plotting functionality.\n\n3. **pandas/core/nanops.py** (lines 1652, 1659): Imports `kendalltau` and `spearmanr` for computing correlation coefficients. These are used in the `get_corr_func` function which supports \"kendall\" and \"spearman\" correlation methods.\n\n4. **pandas/tests/groupby/test_reductions.py** (line 1378): Imports `sem` (standard error of the mean) in the `scipy_sem` helper function used for testing groupby reduction operations.\n\nAll four files contain actual runtime imports of scipy.stats functions (not docstring references). These represent the critical integration points where pandas directly depends on scipy.stats at runtime, and therefore determine where pandas graceful degradation handling is needed when scipy is not installed."
}

